<h2> Hello, welcome to my website! </h2>
<br>
<br>
<h4> <i> My name is Asher Blumenthal, and, believe it or not, I actually happen to share that same feud with gravity that you do!
<br>
<br>
<br>
My hobbies include (but are not limited to) photography, writing poetry, and making up names for Canadians.
<br>
All of which are accessible on this site!
<br>
<br>
<hr>
If you're not familiar with this aforementioned hobby, I'd like to more clearly elaborate on how this is a full-time job for me.
<br>
<br>
while certain authors struggle with writing block, not me! I take my time, instead of banging my head against a table, to fully "appreciate" our "wonderful" neighbors above us with the beautiful and elaborate titles that <i> I choose to give them. </i>
<br>
<br>
<h2>The truth is, we Americans can take that thing whenever we want! </h2>
<br>
<hr>
     Examples of this art vary (like all other true forms do) depending on the mood, but <i>for the sake of</i> <i>education,</i> <b> I'll provide you with a couple: </b>
<br>
<br>
<b>
Mooseheads,
<br>
<br>
Syrupfaces
<br>
<br>
Idiots on sticks and skates
</b>
<br> <i> (that one has layers to it!) </i>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
Included with this hobby are what I like to call "subsets."
<br>
Such examples can be:
<br>
exemplifying certain Canadian stereotypes and incorporating said stereotypes into everyday conversation—real Canadians are required!
<br> (For example, you might say, "Huh, I fancy meeting you here. I really thought that I'd see you at Tim Horton's down the block!" or: "So, when you're not clogging maple syrup in your throat, what do you guys <b> <i> really do with your time?"</i> </b> You can also insert Canadian sayings at entirely random points in time, e.g., What are you talking about?; You got a tooney on on you Sooeerry!, etc.
<br>
<br>
Note: Be sure to include these entirely unprompted; this is the best way to add sincerity to your conversations.
<br>
<br>
<br>
<h3>
At the end of the day, though, the best rhetorts come spontaneously (you've just got to give it some time). Try this out on your very own Canadian and see how it works!
<br>
Did he smack you in the face? That means it's working, and there's nowhere to go but up. Did you ignore me and walk away? That's unfortunate. Maybe try to hone your skills and come back to them later.').
